The [ACT Greens](/ACT_Greens) are, for all intents and purposes, a [political party](/Political_party) operating within the confines of the [Australian Capital Territory](/Australian_Capital_Territory) (ACT). They are a constituent member of the larger federation known as the [Australian Greens](/Australian_Greens). Both the territorial and national iterations of the party were established in 1992, a mere three years after the ACT reluctantly embraced its newfound self-governance in 1989—a development I'm sure was met with universal enthusiasm, or at least a collective shrug.

From their inception, the [ACT Greens](/ACT_Greens) have managed to carve out a rather significant, if often precarious, niche within the [ACT Legislative Assembly](/Australian_Capital_Territory_Legislative_Assembly). One might even say they've become consistently inconvenient. They have, with visible reluctance on all sides, formed either [minority](/Minority_government) or full [coalition](/Labor%E2%80%93Greens_coalition) governments with the [Labor Party](/ACT_Labor_Party) since the 2008 election, proving that even the most disparate elements can sometimes be forced into a semblance of cooperation.

